
CHAPTER XIX.

"On the morrow of that Monday, Earnshaw
being still unable to follow his ordinary em-
ployments, and, therefore, remaining about
the house, I speedily found it would be imprac-
ticable to retain my charge beside me, as here-
tofore.

She got down stairs before me, and out into
the garden; where she had seen her cousin per-
forming some easy work; and when I went to
bid them come to breakfast, I saw she had per-
suaded him to clear a large space of ground
